Why Hopping is the ultimate dynamic movement! Here are multiple Hop variations. A mixture of super reactiveâ¡ï¸, some slower, some for more distance â¡ï¸ others for height â¬ï¸ etc. They all share the most common factor in being that they are a unilateral plyometric, moving on just a single leg. Thatâs important to think about when placing unilateral or single leg movements under that umbrella. 
There are 2 variations in unilateral movements - what I term Bounds (one leg to the other) and Hops (one leg to the same), both single leg movements but vastly different in what they deliver. Bounds sit under a Bipedal format of locomotion (we humansðââï¸ are bipedal and we move around on 2 legs), where as Hops are Unipedal in nature (a one limbed animal although not many - it would be how a dolphin ð¬ or fish may hop upright along on land) and tend not to be well suited for land endeavour. Because of this, Hopping is a much more difficult form of locomotion. Whilst Hopping, the limb has to move at twice the speed and because of this forces are often twice that of a bounding movement, which in turn requires us to deal which much greater forces than a bound, but in order to maintain speed we have to keep the ground contact time as fast. In doing so the stability of the foot upon landing has to initiate at a much faster rate. The best hoppers in world will be preparing to land by pre-activating the lower limb muscles far longer before they would in bounds and this is all because of how much easier bounding can be for locomotion and moving well within sport. 
So before you take yourself or an athlete a step up in plyos or movement in general by adding in unilateral/1-legged movement donât just assume that if they can Bound then Hopping will be fine too. Think about the much greater forces, faster limb speed and faster stabilisation, because theyâre all super important for Hopping and more importantly dynamic sport, but take your time to prescribe.
